# Rust Logging & Tracing

Use `tracing` for all instrumentation. It supersedes the `log` crate and is the ecosystem standard.

## Crate selection

| Crate | Role |
|---|---|
| `tracing` | Instrumentation API — use this in libraries and application code |
| `tracing-subscriber` | Subscriber (sink) wiring — use this in binaries and integration tests only |
| `tracing-appender` | Non-blocking file appender for production |
| `tracing-bunyan-formatter` | JSON output for structured log ingestion |
| `tracing-opentelemetry` | Export spans to OpenTelemetry collectors |

Never use `println!` or `eprintln!` for observability. Never use the `log` crate in new code.

## Log levels — when to use each

| Level | Use for |
|---|---|
| `error!` | Unrecoverable errors that require immediate attention |
| `warn!` | Recoverable but unexpected conditions; degraded operation |
| `info!` | Key lifecycle events (server started, job completed, user action) |
| `debug!` | Detailed operational state useful during development |
| `trace!` | Very high-frequency, per-item detail (loop bodies, hot paths) |

`info!` should be sparse enough to read in production. `debug!` / `trace!` must be free to leave in the codebase — they are compiled out at the subscriber level.

## Structured fields

Always log structured key-value fields rather than interpolated strings:

```rust
// BAD — unstructured, hard to query
info!("Processing request {} for user {}", req_id, user_id);

// GOOD — structured fields
info!(request_id = %req_id, user_id = %user_id, "Processing request");
```

- Use `%` for `Display` values, `?` for `Debug` values, plain assignment for primitives
- Attach IDs, counts, and durations as fields — not embedded in the message string
- Keep the message string constant and human-readable; put the variables in fields

## `#[instrument]`

Use `#[instrument]` to automatically create a span for a function:

```rust
use tracing::instrument;

#[instrument(skip(db), fields(user_id = %req.user_id))]
async fn handle_request(req: Request, db: &Database) -> Result<Response> {
    // span is active for the duration of this function
    debug!("Validating request");
    let user = db.get_user(req.user_id).await?;
    info!(role = %user.role, "User authenticated");
    Ok(process(user))
}
```

- `skip(arg)` to exclude sensitive or large arguments from the span
- `fields(key = value)` to add extra structured fields to the span
- Use `#[instrument(level = "debug")]` for noisy functions so they only appear at debug level
- Do not `#[instrument]` extremely hot inner-loop functions — span creation has overhead

## Subscriber setup (binaries only)

```rust
use tracing_subscriber::{fmt, EnvFilter, layer::SubscriberExt, util::SubscriberInitExt};

fn init_tracing() {
    tracing_subscriber::registry()
        .with(EnvFilter::try_from_default_env().unwrap_or_else(|_| "info".into()))
        .with(fmt::layer().json())  // structured JSON for production
        .init();
}
```

- Configure subscribers only in `main` or test harness — never in library code
- Use `EnvFilter` so log levels are controlled at runtime via `RUST_LOG=myapp=debug,warn`
- Use `.json()` in production; use `.pretty()` or `.compact()` during local development

## Spans and context propagation

- Create spans explicitly for logical units of work that cross function boundaries:
  ```rust
  let span = tracing::info_span!("database_query", table = %table_name);
  let _guard = span.enter(); // synchronous code
  // OR
  async_fn().instrument(span).await; // async code
  ```
- Use `.instrument(span)` on futures — never `.enter()` across `.await` points (it will attach the wrong span to resumed tasks)
- Propagate trace context across service boundaries with `tracing-opentelemetry` + W3C TraceContext headers

## Libraries

- Libraries must never call `tracing_subscriber::init()` or configure any subscriber
- Libraries call `tracing::info!(...)` etc. — the application decides how/where to emit events
- Gate expensive span construction behind `tracing::enabled!(Level::DEBUG)` checks in hot paths
